  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Use&amp;nbsp;Task Effort to&amp;nbsp;compare the planned, baseline, and actual effort for summary tasks for the project.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    This helps to determine if tasks are exceeding their planned effort, which could negatively impact the project.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Summary tasks are used to provide a logical grouping of related project tasks (usually described as subtasks of the&#xD;
    parent summary task).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Definition&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For each summary task:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Planned effort - the effort value from the latest plan&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        First baseline effort - effort value from the first saved baseline of the plan&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Actual effort - the amount of work actually performed.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Analysis&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A good way to monitor Task Effort&amp;nbsp;is to use a bar chart. Plot effort on the Y axis and summary tasks on the X&#xD;
    axis. Include each task with its planned, baseline, and actual effort.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Although there are usually differences, large discrepancies might indicate inaccurate planning, changes in project&#xD;
    scope or requirements, greater than anticipated complexity, or some other factor.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Below is an example of a Task Schedule report for the Online Auction project in Smarter Planet program. The below&#xD;
    diagram shows planned, baseline,&amp;nbsp;and actual effort in person hours for&amp;nbsp;various tasks. &amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
